10426nam a22015255i 9783110218442DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979731448  a97831102184427 a10.1515/97831102184422doi  a(DE-B1597)36333  a(OCoLC)642692803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP324b.L63 2009 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a41200aLoanwords in the World's Languages :bA Comparative Handbook /ced. by Martin Haspelmath, Uri Tadmor. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (1081 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is the first work to address the question of what kinds of words get borrowed in a systematic and comparative perspective. It studies lexical borrowing behavior on the basis of a world-wide sample of 40 languages, both major languages and minor languages, and both languages with heavy borrowing and languages with little lexical influence from other languages. The book is the result of a five-year project bringing together a unique group of specialists of many different languages and areas. The introductory chapters provide a general up-to-date introduction to language contact at the word level, as well as a presentation of the project's methodology. All the chapters are based on samples of 1000-2000 words, elicited by a uniform meaning list of 1460 meanings. The combined database, comprising over 70,000 words, is published online at the same time as the book is published. For each word, information about loanword status is given in the database, and the 40 case studies in the book describe the social and historical contact situations in detail. The final chapter draws general conclusions about what kinds of words tend to get borrowed, what kinds of word meanings are particularly resistant to borrowing, and what kinds of social contact situations lead to what kinds of borrowing situations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aHistorische Linguistik. 4aLexikologie. 4aSprachwandel. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aHistorical Linguistics.  aLanguage Change.  aLexicology.1 aAdelaar, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdelaar, Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlves, Mark J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAwagana, Ari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakker, Dik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartels, Hauke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Cecil H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChumakina, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComrie, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElšík, Viktor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpps, Patience, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstrada Fernández, Zarina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolluscio, Lucía A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Anthony P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGómez Rendón, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaspelmath, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaspelmath, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt